\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.1 Source of Truth and Document Authority
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\series bold
Elko County Information Operations Policy Manual
\series default
 (maintained as the master 
\shape italic
Policy_Manual.lyx
\shape default
 file) is the designated 
\series bold
Authoritative System of Record
\series default
 for all governance controls.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Master Repository
\series default
:
 The LyX source file constitutes the legally authoritative master record.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Public Records Status
\series default
:
 Designation of an "authoritative" copy is for version control only and does not alter public records status,
 retention obligations,
 or disclosure requirements applicable to records in any medium under NRS 239.010.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Operational Interface (System of Engagement)
\series default
:
 The Departmental Knowledge Base (Redmine) serves as the accessible operational interface for day-to-day reference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Synchronization
\series default
:
 Content published in Redmine shall be sourced directly from the LyX master.
 In the event of a discrepancy,
 the LyX master record (and its compiled PDF) takes precedence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.2 Policy Document Structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All policies within the Information Operations Policy Manual shall adhere to the following six-section structure,
 presented in this exact order.
 No sections shall be omitted,
 reordered,
 or renamed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Purpose
\series default
:
 A concise statement defining what the policy governs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Scope
\series default
:
 Defines who and what the policy applies to,
 and what it does not.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Roles and Responsibilities
\series default
:
 Identifies specific roles tasked with execution or oversight.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Compliance and Exceptions
\series default
:
 Defines assessment mechanisms,
 enforcement authority,
 and the exception process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
References
\series default
:
 Citations of upstream frameworks and internal cross-references that are directly cited in the body of the policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Policy Statement
\series default
:
 The core directives,
 organized into subsections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Subsections within the Policy Statement shall use decimal notation (e.g.,
 6.1,
 6.2).
 Nesting beyond two levels (e.g.,
 6.1.1) is prohibited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.3 Purpose Section Template
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Purpose section shall consist of one (1) sentence,
 or two (2) sentences at maximum.
 It shall answer a single question:
 what does this policy govern?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Opening Construction
\series default
:
 Every Purpose statement shall open with the construction "This policy [verb]s..." using a direct,
 present-tense verb (e.g.,
 "This policy establishes...," "This policy defines...," "This policy governs...").
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Prohibited Constructions
\series default
:
 The preamble "The purpose of this policy is to..." is prohibited.
 Introductory filler,
 risk justification,
 and framework alignment rationale shall not appear in the Purpose section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Rationale Placement
\series default
:
 Context that explains why the policy matters,
 what risk it addresses,
 or how it aligns with external frameworks shall be placed in the opening paragraph of Section 6 (Policy Statement) or in the Policy Matrix appendix.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.4 Scope Section Template
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Scope section shall open with a single universal applicability statement using the construction "This policy applies to [who/what]."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When boundary clarification is required,
 the Scope section shall use the following labeled subsections,
 formatted as bolded bullet labels with sub-bullets:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
In Scope
\series default
:
 Capitalized noun phrases identifying what the policy governs.
 Each item shall appear as a sub-bullet beneath the label and consist of a standalone noun phrase with a terminal period.
 No policy pointers are required,
 as the governed items reside within this policy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Out of Scope
\series default
:
 Capitalized noun phrases identifying what the policy does not govern.
 Each item shall appear as a sub-bullet beneath the label,
 followed by a colon and the routing pointer to the governing policy.
 Format:
 "[Topic]:
 
\series bold
Policy [X.XX]
\series default
."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not every policy requires both In Scope and Out of Scope subsections.
 Simple policies where the applicability sentence is sufficient may omit them.
 However,
 when boundaries are drawn,
 they shall be drawn with labels and sub-bullets,
 not with narrative prose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Cross-references within the Scope section shall use the routing pointer format prescribed above.
 The first-use parenthetical title convention defined in Section 6.9 applies to prose references in Sections 3,
 4,
 and 6;
 it does not apply to Scope section routing pointers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Exclusion
\series default
:
 The Scope section shall not contain directives,
 compliance language,
 or enforcement statements.
 Those belong in Section 4.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.5 Roles and Responsibilities Section Template
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Roles and Responsibilities section shall identify every role with accountability under the policy.
 Roles shall be listed in descending order of authority (e.g.,
 IT Director,
 County Manager,
 Assistant IT Director,
 then operational roles,
 then external stakeholders).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each role shall be formatted as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The role title shall appear as a bolded bullet item followed by a colon.
 No text shall follow the colon on the role title line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each distinct obligation shall appear as a sub-bullet beneath the role,
 opening with the word "Shall" and containing exactly one (1) directive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Obligations shall not be chained together in a single comma-separated sentence.
 Each auditable obligation requires its own sub-bullet.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Role Identity Requirement
\series default
:
 Every role listed in Section 3 shall correspond to a defined position in 
\series bold
Policy 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "pol:1.07"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
 (Workforce Roles,
 Responsibilities,
 and Competency Framework),
 an established County institutional title (e.g.,
 County Manager,
 Board of County Commissioners),
 or a defined group with a clear membership boundary (e.g.,
 "All Information Operations Personnel," "All County Personnel," "Department Heads").
 Descriptive activity labels (e.g.,
 "Policy Authors," "Approving Authorities," "System Owners") shall not be used as role identifiers in Section 3.
 If a responsibility applies to any person performing a given activity,
 it shall be assigned to the defined role or group that performs that activity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Roles and Responsibilities section shall focus on ownership of outcomes,
 not step-by-step procedures.
 Procedural detail belongs in Section 6.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.6 Compliance and Exceptions Section Template
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Compliance and Exceptions section shall open with a single sentence establishing the mandatory nature of the policy (e.g.,
 "Compliance with this policy is mandatory for all Information Operations personnel involved in [relevant activity].").
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The section shall contain the following three (3) mandatory labeled bullet items,
 in this order:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Assessment
\series default
:
 Identifies how and when compliance with this policy is evaluated.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Enforcement
\series default
:
 Identifies the consequences of non-compliance and the authority that enforces the policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Exceptions
\series default
:
 Defines the process for requesting deviations.
 Shall state that oral exceptions are not valid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Additional labeled bullets may be included when the policy warrants them.
 The following are the governed set of optional labels:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Constructive Notice
\series default
:
 For policies where publication constitutes notice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Emergency Deviations
\series default
:
 For policies with time-critical override procedures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Sanctions
\series default
:
 For policies with specific disciplinary consequences beyond the standard enforcement framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Universal Applicability
\series default
:
 For policies that apply regardless of location or work status.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Mandatory Compliance
\series default
:
 For policies that apply without exception to all personnel classes.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No other labels shall be introduced without IT Director approval and incorporation into this governing list.
 The Compliance and Exceptions section shall not use numbered subsections (e.g.,
 4.1,
 4.2);
 it shall use the flat bolded-bullet-label structure defined above.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.7 References Section Template
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The References section is the legal and framework audit trail.
 It shall be formatted as a flat list of citation line items with no narrative prose.
 The section shall be divided into two (2) labeled subsections:
 Cited References and Framework Alignment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Cited References
\series default
:
 This subsection contains citations that are directly referenced by number or identifier in the body of the policy (Sections 1 through 4 and Section 6).
 A policy or framework that is not cited in the body text shall not appear in this subsection.
 Conversely,
 any policy or framework cited by number in the body text shall have a corresponding entry in this subsection.
 Cited References are load-bearing —
 they support specific directives,
 cross-references,
 or compliance statements within the policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Framework Alignment
\series default
:
 This subsection contains framework mappings that establish where the policy sits in the broader governance landscape,
 regardless of whether they are explicitly cited in the body text.
 Framework Alignment entries support traceability,
 feed the Policy Matrix (Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.02"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

),
 and make governance alignment visible at the policy level.
 A framework reference that is directly cited in the body text shall appear under Cited References,
 not Framework Alignment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Default Placement
\series default
:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The following categories shall default to Cited References unless they are not cited in the body text:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
ECIO Policies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ECIO Appendices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NRS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NAC.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
LRDA.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CJIS.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NIST CSF.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NIST SP.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The following categories shall default to Framework Alignment unless they are directly cited by identifier in the body text:
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
COBIT 2019.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ITIL v4.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
A COBIT or ITIL reference that is directly invoked by identifier in the body text shall be promoted to Cited References.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Ordering
\series default
:
 Within each subsection,
 citations shall follow the categorical sequence and sub-ordering rules defined in Section 6.11 of this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Formatting Rules
\series default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each citation shall be a distinct,
 individual line item.
 Citations shall not be grouped on a single line.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Reference line items shall not end with a terminal period.
 They are citations,
 not sentences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Internal ECIO policy and appendix references shall not be bolded in either subsection.
 All citation line items shall receive uniform formatting to avoid visually privileging internal references over upstream frameworks.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Internal ECIO policy and appendix references shall use LyX cross-reference insets (CommandInset ref) to maintain link integrity.
 They shall not be manually typed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Citation Syntax
\series default
:
 Citation formatting for each framework category is defined in Section 6.11 of this policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.8 Policy Statement Section Template
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Policy Statement is the operational core of the policy,
 containing the auditable controls and directives.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Framing Preamble
\series default
:
 When a policy requires contextual framing —
 risk justification,
 framework alignment rationale,
 or dual-audience explanation —
 that context shall appear as an opening paragraph or paragraphs before Section 6.1 begins,
 or as the opening content of Section 6.1 itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Subsection Organization
\series default
:
 Content shall be organized into labeled subsections (6.1,
 6.2,
 etc.) grouped by operational sub-domain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
One Directive Per Item
\series default
:
 Each numbered or bulleted item within the Policy Statement shall contain exactly one (1) directive or requirement.
 Blended rules that combine multiple obligations in a single item are prohibited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.9 Compliance Language Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To ensure clear enforceability during audits,
 the following terminology definitions apply to all policy documents within the Information Operations Policy Manual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
"Shall" or "Must"
\series default
:
 Indicates a mandatory requirement.
 Non-compliance is auditable and enforceable.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
"Should"
\series default
:
 Indicates a recommended best practice.
 Deviations from "Should" requirements shall be documented in writing and approved by the IT Director or Policy Owner prior to implementation.
 Justifications shall be retained for audit.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
"May"
\series default
:
 Indicates a permissible or discretionary action.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Anchoring Requirement
\series default
:
 Every directive shall be anchored to a specific,
 capitalized role.
 Orphaned directives (e.g.,
 "Logs shall be reviewed weekly" with no identified role) are prohibited.
 The correct form is "The Systems Administrator shall review logs weekly."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

