\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.10 Universal Style and Grammar Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following style and grammar rules apply to all text within the Information Operations Policy Manual.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Voice and Tense
\series default
:
 All policy text shall use present-tense,
 active voice (e.g.,
 "The IT Director reviews logs" rather than "Logs are reviewed by the IT Director").
 Passive constructions are permitted only when the acting role is genuinely irrelevant or unknown.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Time and Quantity Syntax
\series default
:
 All deadlines,
 timeframes,
 and quantities shall be written as the number in words followed immediately by the numerical digit in parentheses (e.g.,
 "five (5) business days," "twenty-four (24) hours," "ninety (90) calendar days").
 Neither the word nor the digit shall appear alone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Institutional Capitalization
\series default
:
 The following shall always be capitalized:
 proper nouns,
 official job titles (e.g.,
 "IT Director," "Systems Administrator"),
 institutional concepts (e.g.,
 "County," "Department," "Information Operations Department"),
 defined terms from the Glossary (
\series bold
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
),
 and named policy constructs (e.g.,
 "Incident Commander," "Hard Fork," "Operational Handback").
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Acronym Protocol
\series default
:
 The first instance of a technical term or organizational name within each policy shall be fully spelled out,
 followed by its abbreviation in parentheses (e.g.,
 "Criminal Justice Information Services (CJIS)").
 Subsequent references within the same policy may use the abbreviation alone.
 Acronym definitions do not carry across policies;
 each policy shall define its own terms on first use.
 Standard terms defined in the Glossary (
\series bold
Appendix 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "app:6.01"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset


\series default
) are exempt from the first-use requirement only when the policy explicitly states reliance on the Glossary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Oxford Comma
\series default
:
 The Oxford comma is mandatory in all lists (e.g.,
 "systems,
 services,
 and infrastructure").
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Official Systems Terminology
\series default
:
 Software and platforms referenced in policy documents shall be cited by their governance function label only (e.g.,
 "System of Engagement," "Authoritative System of Record," "Endpoint Protection Platform," "Productivity Suite").
 Vendor and product names shall not appear in policy text.
 Product-specific names,
 configurations,
 and implementation details belong in operational documentation maintained in the System of Engagement.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Policy Numbering
\series default
:
 Policy numbers shall follow a strictly padded two-digit decimal system within each chapter (e.g.,
 Policy 1.01,
 Policy 2.05,
 Policy 3.14).
 Single-digit policy numbers (e.g.,
 Policy 1.1) are prohibited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.11 Cross-Reference,
 Citation,
 and Bold Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Cross-Reference Syntax
\series default
:
 Internal references to other policies shall use the following rules:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every reference shall use the singular construction "Policy [X.XX]" (e.g.,
 "Policy 2.04").
 The word "Policy" shall appear before every number,
 even when citing multiple policies in sequence (e.g.,
 "Policy 3.03 and Policy 3.04," never "Policies 3.03 and 3.04").
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first reference to an internal policy within each policy shall include the parenthetical title immediately after the cross-reference (e.g.,
 "Policy 1.08 (Delegation of Authority and Decision Rights)").
 The parenthetical title shall not be bolded;
 bold applies only to the cross-reference itself.
 All subsequent references within the same policy shall use the short form only (e.g.,
 "Policy 1.08").
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Every in-body cross-reference (Sections 1 through 4 and Section 6) shall be bolded and implemented as a LyX cross-reference inset (CommandInset ref) to maintain link integrity.
 Manually typed policy numbers are prohibited in the body of any policy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cross-references within Section 5 (References) shall not be bolded,
 consistent with the uniform citation formatting rule in Section 6.7.
 They shall still use LyX cross-reference insets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Directional phrases such as "see below," "see above," "as described later," and hard-coded page numbers are prohibited.
 All internal references shall use absolute numerical pointers (e.g.,
 "Policy 2.04" or "Section 6.2").
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
External Framework First-Use Syntax
\series default
:
 The first reference to an external framework citation within each policy shall include the full citation with parenthetical topic (e.g.,
 "NIST SP 800-53 Rev.
 5:
 IR-4 (Incident Handling)").
 Subsequent references within the same policy may use the short form (e.g.,
 "NIST SP 800-53 IR-4" or the control identifier alone if context is unambiguous).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Reference Citation Syntax
\series default
:
 Citations within Section 5 (References) shall follow the formatting defined below for each framework category.
 These formats apply uniformly within both the Cited References and Framework Alignment subsections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Internal Policies:
 ECIO Policy [Number]:
 [Policy Title]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Internal Appendices:
 ECIO Appendix [Number]:
 [Appendix Title]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NRS:
 NRS [Chapter].[Section] ([Short Topic Description])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NAC:
 NAC [Chapter].[Section] ([Short Topic Description])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
LRDA:
 LRDA [LRDA Number] ([Record Series Title])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
CJIS:
 CJIS Security Policy v[Version]:
 Section [ID] ([Topic])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NIST CSF:
 NIST CSF [Version]:
 [Function].[Category]-[ID] ([Title])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
NIST SP:
 NIST SP [Number] Rev.
 [Revision]:
 [Control ID] ([Control Title])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
COBIT 2019:
 COBIT 2019:
 [Process ID] ([Process Name])
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
ITIL v4:
 ITIL v4:
 [Practice Name]
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Reference Sub-Ordering Within Categories
\series default
:
 The following ordering rules apply within each subsection (Cited References and Framework Alignment) independently.
 Citations shall not be interleaved across subsections.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
ECIO Policies
\series default
:
 Sorted numerically by Policy Number in ascending order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
ECIO Appendices
\series default
:
 Sorted numerically by Appendix Number in ascending order.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
State of Nevada
\series default
:
 Grouped by authority in the sequence NRS,
 NAC,
 then LRDA.
 Within each group,
 sorted numerically by Chapter,
 Schedule Number,
 or LRDA Number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
CJIS
\series default
:
 Sorted alphanumerically by Section or Control Family identifier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
NIST CSF
\series default
:
 Sorted by Core Function sequence (GV,
 ID,
 PR,
 DE,
 RS,
 RC),
 then alphanumerically by Category and Subcategory identifier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
NIST SP
\series default
:
 Sorted numerically by Publication Number (e.g.,
 SP 800-37 precedes SP 800-53),
 then alphanumerically by Control Identifier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
COBIT 2019
\series default
:
 Sorted alphanumerically by Core Model Objective or Domain identifier.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
ITIL v4
\series default
:
 Sorted alphabetically by Practice name.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\series bold
Other Frameworks
\series default
:
 Sorted alphabetically by issuing authority,
 then publication title.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This ordering establishes structural consistency and does not alter the legal hierarchy of authority established in the Manual Executive Summary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Bold Usage
\series default
:
 Bold formatting is a navigational and structural tool,
 not an emphasis tool.
 Bold shall be reserved for the following uses only:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Internal Cross-References
\series default
:
 Bolded on every instance in the policy body (Sections 1 through 4 and Section 6).
 Not bolded in Section 5 (References).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Glossary-Defined Terms
\series default
:
 Bolded on first use within each policy only.
 Not linked to the Glossary;
 the bold treatment serves as a visual flag that the term carries a specific defined meaning.
 The criteria for Glossary inclusion are defined in Section 6.14.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Structural Labels
\series default
:
 Role titles in Section 3,
 compliance labels in Section 4,
 In Scope and Out of Scope labels in Section 2,
 and contextual clarifier tags (defined in Section 6.12).
 Bolded by virtue of their structural position.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Bold shall not be applied to external framework references (CJIS,
 NIST,
 COBIT control IDs),
 numerical values,
 parenthetical titles accompanying cross-references,
 or general emphasis within prose.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
6.12 List and Structural Formatting Standards
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Terminal Periods
\series default
:
 Every bulleted and sub-bulleted list item shall end with a terminal period,
 regardless of whether the item is a full sentence or a fragment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Exception
\series default
:
 Citation line items in Section 5 (References) shall not end with a terminal period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Bulleted Lists vs.
 Numbered Lists
\series default
:
 Bulleted lists (Itemize) shall be used for unordered collections of items.
 Numbered lists (Enumerate) shall be used only when the items represent an ordered sequence where position is meaningful (e.g.,
 a workflow,
 a hierarchy of precedence).
 Numbered lists shall not be used solely for the purpose of counting items.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Sub-Bullets
\series default
:
 Nested list items shall use the LyX begin_deeper environment (rendered as indented sub-bullets).
 Nesting beyond two levels is prohibited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Bold Label Formatting
\series default
:
 When a bold label is used to identify a bullet item,
 a paragraph-level directive,
 or a topic block within a subsection,
 the label shall always be followed by a colon,
 never a period.
 The colon signals that the label identifies the content that follows.
 Bold labels followed by periods are prohibited.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Contextual Clarifiers
\series default
:
 When a directive requires boundary-setting,
 explanation,
 or qualification,
 the clarifying statement shall be separated from the primary directive using a bolded tag followed by a colon,
 placed on a new line or as a sub-bullet.
 The following tags constitute the governed vocabulary of permitted contextual clarifiers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Constraint
\series default
:
 Defines a hard limitation or boundary condition on the directive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Rationale
\series default
:
 Provides the justification for a requirement that may not be self-evident.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Exception
\series default
:
 Identifies a specific,
 defined circumstance under which the directive does not apply.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Exclusion
\series default
:
 Carves out a specific item,
 group,
 or system from the scope of the directive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize

\series bold
Clarification
\series default
:
 Resolves a potential ambiguity in the directive's application.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No other contextual clarifier tags shall be introduced without IT Director approval and incorporation into this governed list.
\end_layout

